      interview: [
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is the N+1 problem?", a: "It happens when you fetch N objects and then for each object, you perform an additional query to get related data (1 + N queries total).", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "How do you fix N+1 in Django?", a: "By using select_related() or prefetch_related() to fetch all needed data in the first query.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is an index in a database?", a: "A data structure that improves the speed of data retrieval operations on a table at the cost of slower writes and additional space.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "Difference between select_related and prefetch_related?", a: "select_related uses JOINs, prefetch_related uses separate queries.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "When would you add an index to a model field?", a: "When that field is frequently used in filter() or order_by() queries.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is django-debug-toolbar?", a: "A development tool that helps profile SQL queries and other performance metrics per request.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What does 'only()' do in a QuerySet?", a: "It restricts the fields returned from the DB to only specified ones, reducing bandwidth and memory.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What does 'defer()' do in a QuerySet?", a: "It tells Django NOT to load certain fields (like large TextFields) until actually accessed.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is a 'Database JOIN'?", a: "Combining data from two or more tables based on a related column.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "How do you see the SQL for a queryset in the shell?", a: "print(queryset.query).", type: "Coding" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is the cost of Many-to-Many queries compared to ForeignKeys?", a: "They are slower because they require joining through an intermediary table.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is 'Database Denormalization'?", a: "Intentionally adding redundant data to a schema to improve query performance.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "Wait, does 'all()' hit the database?", a: "No, 'all()' just returns a QuerySet. It's lazy. Evaluation hits the DB.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is the 'Exists' lookup?", a: "A way to check if a specific record exists without loading its data.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Junior", q: "What is the 'pk' alias?", a: "Short for 'primary key', automatically maps to whichever field is the PK.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "Difference between select_related and prefetch_related?", a: "select_related uses an SQL JOIN (1 query) and works on single-value relations. prefetch_related does a separate query (2 queries total) and works on multi-value relations.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "How do you use the explain() method?", a: "Call it on a queryset: MyModel.objects.filter(...).explain(). It returns the database's strategy for finding the data.", type: "Coding" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "When should you NOT use an index?", a: "On columns with very low cardinality (like boolean fields) or in tables that are updated very frequently.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "What is the Django Debug Toolbar?", a: "A development tool that gives you a detailed breakdown of SQL queries, execution time, and potential N+1 issues for every request.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "Explain the 'Prefetch' object usage.", a: "It allows you to control the prefetching process, such as applying a specific queryset (with filter/order) to the related objects.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "How do you handle N+1 when using a 'property' in a model that hits the DB?", a: "You should use 'annotate' or prefetch for the needed data instead of doing logic in a property during loops.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "Explain 'Composite Indexes' in Django.", a: "Defined in Meta.indexes, it creates a single index covering multiple columns, useful for queries filtering by both fields.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "What is 'iterator()' and when to use it?", a: "A method that fetches rows one-by-one from the DB. Use it for processing massive datasets to save memory.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "How do you optimize a query that counts objects in a Many-to-Many relationship?", a: "Using annotate(count=Count('m2m_field')) instead of calling .count() on each instance.", type: "Coding" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "What is 'Partial Indexing' and how to implement it?", a: "Creating an index for only a subset of rows (e.g., active users). Use Meta.indexes with a 'condition' argument.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "How do you perform a 'Bulk Update' for performance?", a: "Using MyModel.objects.bulk_update(instances, ['field1', 'field2']) to perform a single SQL update for many rows.", type: "Coding" },
        { level: "Mid", q: "What is the difference between select_related('a', 'b') and select_related('a__b')?", a: "The first joins both A and B to the main model; the second joins A then joins B to A.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "Explain 'Prefetch' objects with custom querysets.", a: "You can pass a Prefetch() object to prefetch_related to further filter or order the related items (e.g., fetch only active comments).", type: "Coding" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "How would you optimize a query involving millions of rows?", a: "Indexes, select_related, using values() to reduce object creation, and potentially using database views or denormalization.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "What is the cost of select_related on large tables?", a: "It creates large result sets due to the JOIN, which can consume significant memory and database processing power.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "Can you use select_related for a reverse ForeignKey?", a: "No, you must use prefetch_related because a reverse ForeignKey is a 1-to-many relationship.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "How do you identify duplicate SQL queries in a Django request?", a: "Using the SQL panel of the Debug Toolbar or analysis tools like Sentry.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "Explain 'Database Sharding' versus 'Read Replicas'.", a: "Sharding splits data across multiple DBs based on a key; Read Replicas copy data to secondary DBs for read-only query load balancing.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "How does Django handle 'Database Routing' for multiple DBs?", a: "Using a Router class in settings that implements 'db_for_read', 'db_for_write', and 'allow_migrate' logic.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "Explain 'Materialized Views' and how to use them with Django ORM.", a: "Materialized views are precomputed table-like structures in the DB. Django interacts with them via models with 'managed=False'.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "How do you handle 'Full-Text Search' performance in Django?", a: "Using SearchVector, SearchQuery, and GinIndexes (for Postgres) to enable efficient word-based indexing and ranking.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "What is the 'Queryset.explain()' output format 'COST'?", a: "An abstract unit used by the DB planner to estimate the relative amount of resources (CPU, I/O) a query will take.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "How do you implement 'Caching at the ORM layer' effectively?", a: "Using 'django-cachalot' or 'django-cache-machine' which automatically cache querysets based on table invalidation.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "Explain 'Sequential Scan' versus 'Index Scan' in the explain() output.", a: "Sequential scan reads the whole table from disk; Index scan uses the B-tree to find specific locations (much faster for large tables).", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "How do you optimize 'In-list' queries with thousands of IDs?", a: "By using a temporary table or a subquery instead of a massive 'WHERE id IN (...)' which can hit limits or perform poorly.", type: "Scenario" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "What is the performance difference between .count() and .exists() in Django?", a: ".exists() is slightly faster because it tells the DB to stop searching after finding the very first record.", type: "Conceptual" },
        { level: "Senior", q: "How do you handle 'Lock Contention' in high-concurrency Django apps?", a: "Shorten transactions, use atomic increments (F objects), and use 'select_for_update(nowait=True)' to handle locks gracefully.", type: "Scenario" }
      ]
